    <h2>BWH - Site Conventions</h2>
    <h3>CSS Controlled Media Types...</h3>
    <p>
    Everything mentioned is of course highly dependent on whether your <acronym title='User Agent'>UA</acronym> of choice can handle ( or interpret ) the code used. We test as extensively as we can but if a <acronym title='User Agent'>UA</acronym> is either broken, bugged or incapable of handling the data we apologise but there's not a lot we can do ( at present ) that we have not as yet implemented.
    </p>
    <h3>Screen Conventions:</h3>
    <h4>Styles, Colours etc</h4>
    <p>
    The text is displayed in a mixture of <acronym title='eXtensible HyperText Markup Language'>XHTML</acronym> and <acronym title='Cascading Style Sheets'>CSS</acronym> to control certain elements allowing for a rich display of content. Below is a table outlining the major tags and showcasing their purpose.
    </p>
    <table summary='This is a table outlining which major HTML tags are used for typography purposes throughout this site and showing examples of their use'>
    <tr><th abbr='N'>
      Name:
    </th><th abbr='H/C'>
      XHTML / CSS:
    </th><th abbr='RIP'>
      Result In Page:
    </th></tr><tr class='rowOdd'><td>
      Acronym / Abbreviation
    </td><td>
      <code>&lt;acronym&gt;&lt;/acronym&gt;</code>
    </td><td>
      <acronym title='Test text'>Resulting Text Style &amp; Colour</acronym>
    </td></tr><tr class='rowEven'><td>
      Code &amp; Markup Terms
    </td><td>
      <code>&lt;code&gt;&lt;/code&gt;</code>
    </td><td>
      <code>Resulting Text Style &amp; Colour</code>
    </td></tr><tr class='rowOdd'><td>
      Programme Fragments etc
    </td><td>
      <code>&lt;pre&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;</code>
    </td><td>
      <pre>Resulting Text Style &amp; Colour</pre>
    </td></tr><tr class='rowEven'><td>
      Required Form Fields
    </td><td>
      <code>&lt;foo class='req'&gt;&lt;/foo&gt;</code>
    </td><td>
      <span class='req'>Resulting Text Style &amp; Colour</span>
    </td></tr><tr class='rowOdd'><td>
      Link Text
    </td><td>
      <code>&lt;a href='foo'&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</code>
    </td><td>
      <a href='conventions.html' title='test'>Resulting Text Style &amp; Colour</a>
    </td></tr>
    </table>
    <h3>Print Conventions:</h3>
    <p>
    When printing any BushWise page the Print Style Sheet determines how the page should be displayed ( and ultimately printed ). This includes removing the Page Header, Sidebar &amp; Related navigation panes, whilst adding a small greyscale BushWise logo to the top of the printable document for identification.
    </p><p>
    HyperText links are not visually indicated as such ( not much use on a printed page anyway ) and where applicable ( or possible ), text indicating a link is removed ( not shown ) or alternative text applied.
    </p>
    <h3>Handheld Conventions:</h3>
    <h4>Web enabled Personal Digital Assistant's, Phones etc:</h4>
    <p>
    One word... &#8220;tricky&#8221;. Just when we all thought that catering for the plethora of screen based Browsers was a challenge, handheld devices quite simply come into a league of their own. There are no &#8220;standards&#8221; to speak of regarding just how any of these devices will render ( or rather &#8220;attempt&#8221; to render ) any given data supplied to them. The big issue of course being what is known as &#8220;real estate&#8221; - the amount of screen space available for viewing data flowed into your handheld device of choice. This variable changes quite dramatically and causes developers a bit of a headache. We have gone for the &#8220;keep it small, keep it simple&#8221; approach which seems to work for most scenarios, however some layout devices such as <acronym title='HyperText Markup Language'>HTML</acronym> <code>table</code>'s may, or may not render as visually understandable or indeed &#8220;at all&#8221;.
    </p>
    <h3>Wireless Application Protocol - WAP</h3>
    <p>
    A decision was made not to go down this particular road, it seems a dying ( if not already dead ) means of supporting handheld devices and utilising <acronym title='Cascading Style Sheets'>CSS</acronym> seems a far more practical and ultimately useful tool to maintain a service for these devices.
    </p>
    <h3>Aural &amp; Tactile Feedback:</h3>
    <p>
    An area we are very interested in expanding, whilst quite a bit of research has been done we do not yet have any systems in place to incorporate the appropriate media required as we currently have no access to the hardware devices or software. It would be a great help to communicate to someone ( or persons ) who have access to, are familiar with and are willing to act as a &#8220;guinea pig&#8221; whilst we add the required elements needed to enable access for those with visual difficulties.
    </p>
    <h3>Web Standards:</h3>
    <h4>The World Wide Web Consortium - W3C</h4>
    <p>
    The following documents have been used as the reference materials in the creation of this Site:
    </p>
    <ul>
    <li>
      Cascading Style Sheets, level 2 revision 1 CSS 2.1 Specification
    </li><li>
      HTML 4.01 Specification
    </li><li>
      XHTMLTM 1.0 The eXtensible HyperText Markup Language ( Second Edition )
    </li><li>
      Web Content Accessibility Guidelines 1.0
    </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
    This Site fully 100% conforms to the standards of the first three ( <acronym title='Cascading Style Sheets'>CSS</acronym>, <acronym title='HyperText Markup Language'>HTML</acronym> &amp; <acronym title='eXtensible HyperText Markup Language'>XHTML</acronym> ) and follows as closely as possible the last ( Accessibility Guidelines ).
    </p>
    <h3>Erratum...</h3>
    <h4>Acronyms &amp; Abbreviations</h4>
    <p>
    The <code>acronym</code> tag is used somewhat erroneously in-so-much as abbreviations are also included. The reason for this is simple enough, one, it's easier ( how's that for honesty? ) and two, there has been some debate surrounding certain terms as to whether they are actually acronyms or abbreviations. Some are obvious, some not so. To alleviate this issue all acronyms and abbreviations have been bundled together under the <code>acronym</code> tag.
    </p><p>
    <i>... and here endith the pedantry...</i>
    </p>
